results.name: Lexicographically earliest permutation of the natural numbers such that each term has a common divisor with at least two earlier terms, a(n)=n for n<4.
comment: For n>3: n is prime iff a(n) < a(n-1); a(A112976(n)) = A000040(n).
For n>8, a(n) can be described as follows: all composite numbers in natural order, with primes inserted so that every prime p immediately follows 3p. - _Ivan Neretin_, Apr 26 2015
link: Ivan Neretin, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..1000
Index entries for sequences that are permutations of the natural numbers
